 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=loraffthemage>Loraff the Mage</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 15<br> <font color=#333333>(2/21/03 7:00 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowergeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8848.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Mage friendly</span><hr size=1> Seems like a lot of mages desire such groups, but they lived for so long going it solo, unable to get in groups, it's hard to break the soloing habit.  Recently on Er. Marr server my brother (61 mage) and I (58 mage) have been getting mage groups going in Plane of Innovation.  We've only done it 4 times so far.  We just started sending tells to mages in the right level range who were in a non-exp zone like PoK, PoT or the nexus.  Sometimes they agree to come.  They often join and say &quot;ok, I'll try this but I don't see how it will work...&quot; and when the group finally breaks up they say &quot;please invite me next time, that was fantastic!&quot; or &quot;all the mages in my guild are drooling about getting in to a group like this now!&quot;  It's now getting easier to start such a group, with repeat 'customers.'<br>
<br>
Often there are 1 or 2 other groups at the zone of PoI, and when we get 6 pets going, we invariably get comments from people about how cool it looks, and how fast the mobs drop.  When a 63 monk and 61 warrior stand near the pet 'kill area' to see the hits, and they say &quot;WOW, the pets are awesome&quot; you feel at least your pet is getting some respect. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   We talk to them about calling us to help on bad pulls, and if they need a hand we are glad to help keep the area under control.  They often buff us once we all get to be friendly.  We take non-mages as they come LFG but prefer casters to pure melee due to the aggro and healing they cause and require.  If we get a cleric, we are fine with taking melees.  I hate to exclude people (even Druids and Rangers <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) Our shaman decided that on single pulls, it was useless to slow; things would die in 10-20 seconds much of the time.  His pet actually did quite well too.  Necros and BL's work very well of course.  All the pets get the L61 stun blades, and they knock the mobs all over the place.  (it's fun to see 6-9 pets all working together; they don't get confused and loose the target, they are almost scary the way they kick the crap out of something, then all stop at the exact same time and return to their places...something about the machine-like precision is cool)  And if a pet dies, it's not like loosing a real player.  Aggro tends to spread around so they don't die a lot.<br>
<br>
The highest mage (my L61 brother) pulled.  It goes very well.  We have sub-groups set up to do adds or double pulls.  We simply start a raid party if we go over 6 players.  We are still noobs at this, and make mistakes, but we're getting better.<br>
<br>
I can't recommend my server yet, but this grouping of L53-61 mages has been fun so far.  Maybe it will spread.  Give it a try on your server if you can.  We found that getting just 2 or 3 mages as a dedicated base group makes it easy to get more players to join.  Add a chanter or shammy and you can rock even with just a few mages, but having MORE is when it gets really fun.<br>
<br>
